<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-397-936  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 397 936.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  May 1 1990 v4 n17 p59(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple Pacific's new chief aims for record growth: points to Japanas key to success. (Ian Diery)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Said, Carolyn.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Apple Pacific president Ian Diery, who replaced retiring executiveDelbert Yocam in Oct 1990, says he expects the Pacific Rim toaccount for 25 percent of Apple's revenues by 1995.andP;  Diery notesthat the Japanese market is especially important in achieving thisgrowth because Japan has the world's second largest economy.andO;Japan is crucial in Apple's global strategy, and Diery says thatApple 'won't survive' if it does not become a global firm.andP;  AppleJapan has only 3 percent of the Japanese market despite 80 percentannual growth.andP;  Diery's goal is to increase this share to 10percent by strengthening Apple's distribution network in Asia andencouraging the development of more Japanese-localized software.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (officials and employees).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     International TradeJapanExecutiveManagement.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Ian Diery. (portrait)Person:    Diery, Ian (planning).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Points to Japan as key to successandM;By Carolyn SaidandM;San Francisco -- Spanning Canada, Australia, Latin America, Japan and the FarEast, Apple Pacific is by far the most diverse of Apple's triad ofinternational regions.andM;The region, particularly Japan, is poised for blockbuster growth during thenext few years, according to the new president of Apple Pacific, Ian Diery, anative of Sydney, Australia.andM;Diery, 39, an 11-year veteran of Wang Laboratories Inc. who replaced longtimeApple executive Delbert Yocam at the helm of the Pacific division in October,expects Apple Pacific, which now brings in about 12 percent to 14 percent ofApple's revenues, to account for one-quarter of revenues within four or fiveyears.andM;Japan, the world's second-largest economy, is key to that goal, he said.andO;Diery hopes to make Apple Japan the company's largest subsidiary in theworld.andM;&quot;If we're not successful in Japan, we won't be a global company,&quot; he said.andO;&quot;If we're not a global company, we won't survive.&quot;andM;Apple Japan has been growing at about 80 percent a year, but stakes a claimto only about 3 percent of the Japanese computer market, according to theJapan Electronic Industry Development Association.andP;  Diery wants to commandeera total of 10 percent -- $1 billion worth -- of the Japanese market by 1994.andO;That will also represent 10 percent of Apple's total revenues at that time,he said.andM;Despite the formidable competition posed by Japanese manufacturer NEC Corp.,andO;which controls some 60 percent of the Japanese market, Diery said the cachetof the Apple name appeals to Japanese consumers.andP;  &quot;We're catching a wave ofenthusiasm there -- it's almost cultural,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;The younger generationis catching on to personal computing.&quot;andM;Apple needs more Japanese-localized software as well as a broaderdistribution network to crack the market, Diery said.andM;The new division president, whom colleagues have dubbed &quot;action-point Diery,&quot;outlined several strategies to increase growth in his far-flung jurisdiction.andM;He has already dismantled direct-market sales; all Apple Pacific sales gothrough resellers.andP;  Now he wants to increase reseller efficiency by tyingcompensation to end-user sales rather than inventory; developing better salestraining and clear marketing tools for resellers, such as a new multimediaworkstation called Mentor; and showing resellers why it's to their advantageto sell Apple products.andM;Diery also wants to emphasize the education market to build a future customerbase.andP;  &quot;Eighty percent of our high-end users have used an Apple II sometimein their life,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;It's in our interest to drive the low end.andP;  TheApple II is still a wonderful product.andP;  We also should put the Mac into thatmarket.&quot;andM;Finally, he wants to rebalance Apple Pacific's budget, cutting fixed costswhile increasing demand-driven discretionary spending.andO;</TEXT></DOC>